OK I get it !
For the record, here is a snippet 

```
subtotal_cell = subtotal_row.getCell( "my_cell" );
let subtotal_address = subtotal_cell.address[ 0 ];
subtotal_cell.numFmt = '0.00';
subtotal_cell.value = { formula : `SUM(${ subtotal_address }2:${ subtotal_address }${ lastDataRowCount })` };

subtotal_cell.name = `${ worksheet_name }.${ subtotal_address }${ lastDataRowCount }`;

// Add sum up datas                                                                                       
cell = currentRow.getCell( subtotal_address );
cell.numFmt = '0.00';
// The following don't work. Note that this formula value is used in the cell.name instead.
// cell.value = { formula : `${ worksheet_name }.${ subtotal_address }${ lastDataRowCount }` };
// The following works, strange !
cell.value = { formula : subtotal_cell.name };
```

I couldn't get formulas linking to other worksheets to work, but I managed to work around this via the [Defined names](https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs#defined-names) functionality, as @GregoryNEUT helpfully suggested.

Here is a short snippet illustrating this, in case anyone finds their way to this thread

```js
// Define a named range of cells in the remote worksheet
let cellRangeName = "myCellRange";
for (let i = 2; i <= rowCount; i++) {
  // We set all cells to the same name, which creates a named range
  remoteSheet.getCell(`A${i}`).name = cellRangeName;
}

// ...

// Use the named range in my current sheet formula
sheet.fillFormula(`B2:B${rowCount}`, `${cellRangeName}*2`, () => 0);
```
